<p>Know Your Customer (KYC) verification used to require expensive vendor contracts, months of integration work, and deep expertise in biometrics. In 2026, you can add a complete KYC flow to your app in an afternoon with a <strong>KYC verification API</strong>.</p>

<p>This guide walks you through building a production-ready KYC onboarding flow using OpenBiometrics — from document scanning to selfie verification to liveness detection.</p>

<h2>What is KYC Verification?</h2>

<p>KYC verification is the process of confirming a person's identity, typically required by financial regulations (AML/CFT). A modern KYC flow has three steps:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Document capture</strong> — scan a passport, ID card, or driver's license</li>
  <li><strong>Selfie verification</strong> — match the person's face against the document photo</li>
  <li><strong>Liveness check</strong> — prove the person is physically present (not a photo or deepfake)</li>
</ol>

<h2>The Architecture</h2>

<pre><code>User's phone/browser
    |
    ├── 1. Capture document image
    ├── 2. Extract MRZ / OCR data
    ├── 3. Capture selfie
    ├── 4. Verify face matches document
    └── 5. Liveness check (blink, smile)
    |
    ▼
Your backend → OpenBiometrics API
    |
    ├── POST /documents/scan  → document type, MRZ data, OCR text
    ├── POST /documents/verify → face match score
    └── POST /liveness/sessions → challenge-response anti-spoofing
</code></pre>

<h2>Step 1: Scan the Document</h2>

<p>The <code>/documents/scan</code> endpoint detects the document, corrects perspective, runs OCR, and parses the MRZ zone — all in a single call.</p>

<pre><code>const doc = await ob.documents.scan(documentImage);

console.log(doc.mrz.parsed.surname);      // "SMITH"
console.log(doc.mrz.parsed.document_number); // "AB1234567"
console.log(doc.mrz.parsed.nationality);    // "GBR"
console.log(doc.mrz.check_digits_valid);    // true
</code></pre>

